Project Overview¶

This project analyzes various academic, behavioral, and demographic factors that influence students' semester GPA. The dataset includes 25 features such as study habits, stress indicators, family income, and prior GPA.
The goal is to build a reliable regression model that can predict a student’s semester GPA and understand the key drivers behind academic performance.

!pip install -q catboost xgboost lightgbm

Dataset Overview¶

The dataset contains a mix of academic, behavioral, and demographic features related to undergraduate students.
Key variables include:

  • Study habits (study hours, library usage, sleep hours)
  • Work and financial factors (work hours, scholarship status, financial support)
  • Stress and well-being indicators (stress level, homesickness level, social support score)
  • Academic history (attendance percentage, previous semester GPA)
  • Demographic details (age, country/region, years in the US, visa type)

Our target variable is GPA, which we aim to predict using regression models.

target = "semester_gpa"
X = df.drop(columns=[target])
y = df[target]

feature_names = X.columns.tolist()

scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

models = {
    "LinearRegression": LinearRegression(),
    "Ridge": Ridge(alpha=1.0),
    "Lasso": Lasso(alpha=0.01),
    "ElasticNet": ElasticNet(alpha=0.01, l1_ratio=0.5),
    "BayesianRidge": BayesianRidge(),
    "RandomForest": RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=300, random_state=42),
    "ExtraTrees": ExtraTreesRegressor(n_estimators=300, random_state=42),
    "GradientBoosting": GradientBoostingRegressor(),
    "SVR": SVR(),
    "XGBoost": XGBRegressor(objective='reg:squarederror', n_estimators=300, random_state=42),
    "CatBoost": CatBoostRegressor(verbose=0, random_state=42),
    "LGBM": LGBMRegressor(random_state=42),
}

kf = KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

cv_results = {}

for name, model in models.items():
    r2_scores = cross_val_score(model, X_scaled, y, cv=kf, scoring="r2")
    rmse_scores = -cross_val_score(model, X_scaled, y, cv=kf, scoring="neg_root_mean_squared_error")
    cv_results[name] = {
        "cv_r2_mean": r2_scores.mean(),
        "cv_r2_std": r2_scores.std(),
        "cv_rmse_mean": rmse_scores.mean(),
        "cv_rmse_std": rmse_scores.std()
    }

cv_df = pd.DataFrame(cv_results).T.sort_values("cv_rmse_mean")
cv_df

Selecting and Training the Best Model¶

Based on cross-validation performance, the model with the lowest RMSE is selected as the final model.
We now train this best model on the training set and evaluate it on the test set to measure real-world performance.

best_model_name = cv_df.index[0]
best_model_name

'ElasticNet'
best_model = models[best_model_name]
best_model

ElasticNet(alpha=0.01)

ElasticNet(alpha=0.01)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X_scaled, y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42
)

best_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = best_model.predict(X_test)

final_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
final_r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)

final_rmse, final_r2

Learning Curve¶

The learning curve illustrates how the model’s performance changes as the training size increases.
It helps identify whether the model is overfitting, underfitting, or benefits from more data.

train_sizes, train_scores, val_scores = learning_curve(
    best_model, X_scaled, y, cv=KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=42),
    scoring="r2", train_sizes=np.linspace(0.1, 1.0, 8), n_jobs=-1
)

train_mean = train_scores.mean(axis=1)
val_mean = val_scores.mean(axis=1)

plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.plot(train_sizes, train_mean, marker='o', label="Training R²")
plt.plot(train_sizes, val_mean, marker='s', label="Validation R²")
plt.xlabel("Training Size")
plt.ylabel("R² Score")
plt.title(f"{best_model_name} Learning Curve")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Feature Importance¶

To understand which factors most influence GPA predictions, we examine model-derived feature importance values.
For ElasticNet, the magnitude of coefficients reflects each feature’s contribution.

if hasattr(best_model, "coef_"):
    importances = np.abs(best_model.coef_)
elif hasattr(best_model, "feature_importances_"):
    importances = best_model.feature_importances_
else:
    importances = None

if importances is not None:
    fi = pd.Series(importances, index=feature_names).sort_values(ascending=False)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
    fi.head(15).plot(kind="barh")
    plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
    plt.xlabel("Importance")
    plt.title(f"{best_model_name} — Feature Importance")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    fi
else:
    fi = None
    fi

joblib.dump(encoders, "encoders.pkl")

GPA Prediction Function¶

The function below takes a new student's details as input, applies the saved preprocessing steps, and outputs a predicted semester GPA using the trained model.

def predict_gpa(student_dict):
    df_input = pd.DataFrame([student_dict])

    for col in cat_cols:
        le = encoders[col]
        df_input[col] = le.transform(df_input[col])

    df_input = df_input[feature_names]
    scaled = scaler.transform(df_input)
    pred = best_model.predict(scaled)[0]
    return pred

Conclusion¶

In this project, we built a complete machine learning pipeline to predict students’ semester GPA using academic, behavioral, and demographic features. After evaluating multiple regression models through 5-fold cross-validation, ElasticNet delivered the best overall performance with a strong balance between accuracy and generalization.

Key factors influencing GPA included:

  • Study hours per week
  • Attendance percentage
  • Previous semester GPA
  • Stress and academic pressure
  • Sleep and screen time patterns

The final model demonstrates reliable predictive performance and provides meaningful insights into the factors associated with student success. The prediction function and saved model components enable future use without retraining.
